\f0 Following this argument, I conducted more research in order to forge a template for understanding, for containing a small subgenre of VR within a malleable net of definitions, and thus creating more music-based VR. This research was interesting, but ultimately not fulfilling as it related to music. Due to the music-centric nature of my approach, VR served merely as a vessel, my Kon-Tiki, that ferried me to the opposite shores of greater musical understanding. My journey as researcher paralleled Joseph Campbell\'92s hero\'92s journey: call to adventure (beginning the PhD program), night-sea journey (VR as vessel, research related musical performances), father atonement (linking my discovery with previous researchers in the field), return (putting this experience into words and concepts), and elixir (the dissertation document). This relation was interesting because of the significance I will detail later of Campbell\'92s monomyth as it relates to music.\
